idya Vidya<ref name=\"ITU2\">{{Cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/ca/album/ncs-infinity/1020164722 |title=NCS: Infinity by Various Artists on Apple Music |date=2015-07-31 |language=en-CA |access-date=2018-01-26}}{{unreliable source?|date=November 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Alan Walker (music producer)|Alan Walker]]<ref name=\"BB\"/>\n*Waysons<ref name=\"BWW\"/>\n*Whales {{small|(formerly Sex Whales)}}<ref name=\"BWW\"/>\n*Tom Wilson<ref name=\"ITU3\">{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/ncs-elevate/1463598538 |title=NCS: Elevate by Various Artists on iTunes |language=en-us |access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n*Jim Yosef<ref name=\"BB\"/>\n*Anna Yvette<ref name=\"BB\"/>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:British independent record labels]]\n[[Category:Electronic dance music record labels]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 2011]]\n[[Category:Electronic music record labels]]\n[[Category:English electronic dance music record labels]]\n[[Category:Music-related YouTube Channels]]\n\n\n{{record-label-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Flyabovesky", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eArtists", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NoCopyrightSounds"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Diamond (professor)", "text_new": "'''Andrew Jay Diamond''' (born 1 November 1967) is an American academic and professor of United States history at [[Sorbonne University]], where he directs the research center [http://hdea.paris-sorbonne.fr/ Histoire et dynamique des espaces anglophones].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nDiamond was born in Boston in 1967 and raised in Needham, Massachusetts. He attended [[Tufts University]] (1986-1990), where he majored in History and English. He obtained his PhD in History from the [[University of Michigan in Ann Arbor]] in 2004 with a doctoral dissertation entitled \"Hoodlums, Rebels, and Vice lords: Street Gangs, Youth Subcultures, and Race in Chicago, 1919-1968.\" His doctoral research earned him a fellowship from the [[Harry Frank Guggenheim Foundation]].\n\n== Career ==\nDiamond began his academic career in France in 2002 as a lecturer in American civilization at the [[University of Picardy Jules Verne|Universit\u00e9 de Picardie \u2013 Jules Verne]] and then moved on to the [[Charles de Gaulle University \u2013 Lille III|Universit\u00e9 de Lille 3]] in 2005, where he worked as an Assistant Professor until 2010. Between 2010 and 2012, Diamond was a full research fellow at the [https://www.sciencespo.fr/ceri/fr Centre d'Etudes et de Recherches Internationales (CERI)] at [[Sciences Po|Sciences Po - Paris]], where he also taught a number of classes between 2007 and 2012. In 2012, he obtained his current position at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]].\n\nDiamond has been a member of the editorial boards of the ''[https://www.cairn.info/revue-francaise-d-etudes-americaines.htm Revue fran\u00e7aise d'\u00e9tudes am\u00e9ricaines]'' and ''[https://www.tandfonline.com/toc/rsix20/current The Sixties: A Journal of History, Politics and Culture]'', and served on the Board of Directors of the [https://uha47.wildapricot.org/ Urban History Association] and the [[Franco-American Fulbright Commission|Fulbright Commission]] in France. He has been a featured speaker for the African Regional Services of the [[United States Department of State]], the United States Embassy in Paris, and the Consulate General of France in Chicago. He worked with the [[Institut Fran\u00e7ais]] of the [[French Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] as curator of \"City/Cit\u00e9: A Transatlantic Exchange,\" a program of international conferences that brings together researchers, artists, policymakers, and activists from the United States and France to engage in a dialogue about the current state of urban democracy and of the circumstances arrayed against the realization of democratic ideals.<ref>{{cite web|title=City/Cit\u00e9: A Transatlantic Exchange|url=https://fr.franceintheus.org/spip.php?article8237}}</ref> He has written [https://soundcloud.com/newberrylibrary/chicago-on-the-make-andrew-j-diamond extensively] and appeared regularly in both the French and American mainstream media on issues of race and inequality in France and the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liberation.fr/auteur/4247-andrew-diamond|title=Andrew DIAMOND|website=Lib\u00e9ration.fr|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rfi.fr/fr/ameriques/20190331-chicago-municipales-preckwinkle-lightfoot-diamond|title=A Chicago, deux Afro-Am\u00e9ricaines au second tour des municipales|date=2019-03-31|website=RFI|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20130715-debate-part-1-trayvon-martin-obama-gun-control|title=The Debate - The Zimmerman case: Racial profiling or not?|date=2013-07-15|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbez.org/stories/_/9a20a815-e22b-4352-8983-200d18cd6124|title=Comparing racism and inequality in Paris to Chicago & Detroit|date=2015-11-02|website=WBEZ Chicago|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\nHe is the author or co-author of a number of articles and books on the history of politics, race and political culture. His most recent monograph, ''Chicago on the Make: Power and Inequality in a Modern City'' explores the \"link between race and neoliberalization at Chicago's grassroots over the 20th century\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Chicago on the Make: Power and Inequality in a Modern City|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=o4A0DwAAQBAJ&dq=andrew++J+diamond+opinion+piece&hl=fr&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref> The book was awarded the [http://www.midwesternhistory.com/jon-gjerde-prize Jon Gjerde Prize] for the best book in Midwestern history in 2017 and the [https://www.historyillinois.org/Awards/AnnualAwards.aspx Illinois State Historical Society's Award of Superior Achievement], and was featured in the ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Renn|first=Aaron M.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/20/books/review/andrew-diamond-chicago-on-the-make.html|title=Four Books Explore Various Aspects of Cities Past and Present|date=2018-04-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Le\u00f3n|first=Concepci\u00f3n de|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/16/books/read-these-3-books-about-gun-violence-in-chicago.html|title=Read These 3 Books About Gun Violence in Chicago|date=2018-08-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Major publications ==\nDiamond, Andrew J. and Thomas J. Sugrue, eds., ''Neoliberal Cities: The Remaking of Postwar Urban America'' (New York: New York University Press, 2020)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nyupress.org/9781479832378/neoliberal-cities|title=Neoliberal Cities|website=NYU Press|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\nDiamond, Andrew J., ''Chicago on the Make: Race and Inequality in a Modern City'' (Oakland: University of California Press, 2017)\n\nDiamond, Andrew and Pap Ndiaye, ''Histoire de Chicago'' (Paris: Fayard, 2013)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.fayard.fr/histoire/histoire-de-chicago-9782213642550|title=\"Histoire de chicago\", Andrew Diamond, Pap NDIAYE|date=2020-03-31|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nDiamond, Andrew, J., ''Mean Streets: Chicago Youths and the Everyday Struggle for Empowerment in the Multiracial City, 1908-1969'' (Berkeley and Los Angeles: University of California Press, 2009)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.ucpress.edu/book/9780520257474/mean-streets|title=Mean Streets|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[https://chipublib.bibliocommons.com/events/search/fq=branch_location_id:(15)&fq=types:(52ec53226ea5ed000000000f)/event/58dc0d29d13aea2200b0a0ec Acclaimed historian Andrew J. Diamond returns to CPL to discuss his new book, Chicago on the Make].\n\nChauvin, S. 2014. Chicago et l'exception urbaine am\u00e9ricaine. A propos des Andrew Diamond, Pap Ndiaye, Histoire de Chicago, Fayard in ''[http://www.laviedesidees.fr/Chicago-et-l-exception-urbaine.html La vie des id\u00e9es]''\n\nDuis, P.R. 2012. Mean Streets: Chicago Youths and the Everyday Struggle for Empowerment in the Multiracial City, 1908\u20131969.\n\nHinderer, M. 2010. Mean Streets: Chicago Youths and the Everyday Struggle for Empowerment in the Multiracial City, 1908\u20131969. By Andrew J. Diamond.(Berkeley: University of California Press, 2009. xviii, 396 pp.&nbsp; {{ISBN|978-0520-25747-4}}).\n\nPacyga, D. 2011. 'Review of Diamond, Andrew J., Mean Streets: Chicago Youths and the Everyday Struggle for Empowerment in the Multiracial City, 1908-1969.'  [http://www.h-net.org/reviews/showrev.php?id=32973 H-Urban, H-Net Reviews.]\n\nWesley, J.M. 2010. \"Andrew J. Diamond, Mean Streets: Chicago Youths and the Everyday Struggle for Empowerment in the Multiracial City, 1908\u20131969,\" ''The Journal of African American History'' 95(3-4), pp.&nbsp;451\u2013453.\n\nWieviorka, O. 2013. Critique: Chicaghetto.  ''[http://next.liberation.fr/livres/2013/11/27/chicaghetto_962442 Lib\u00e9ration]''\n\nYoung Jr, A.A., 2010. Mean Streets: Chicago Youths and the Everyday Struggle for Empowerment in the Multiracial City, 1908-1969.\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diamond, Andrew}}\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Paris-Sorbonne University faculty]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American expatriate academics]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Writers from Boston]]\n[[Category:Tufts University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:Historians from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People from Newton, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "'''Andrew Jay Diamond''' (born 1 November 1967) is an American academic and professor of American history and civilization at the [[Universit\u00e9 Paris-Sorbonne]] and also the Director of the [[Histoire et dynamique des espaces Anglophones]] (HDEA).\n\n== Early life and education ==\nDiamond was born in Boston in 1967 and raised in Needham, Massachusetts. He attended [[Tufts University]] (1986-1990), where he majored in History and English. He obtained his PhD in History from the [[University of Michigan in Ann Arbor]] in 2004 with a doctoral dissertation entitled \"Hoodlums, Rebels, and Vice lords: Street Gangs, Youth Subcultures, and Race in Chicago, 1919-1968.\" His doctoral research earned him a fellowship from the [[Harry Frank Guggenheim Foundation]].\n\n== Career ==\nDiamond began his academic career in France in 2002 as a lecturer in American civilization at the [[Universit\u00e9 de Picardie \u2013 Jules Verne]] and then moved on to the [[Universit\u00e9 de Lille 3]] in 2005, where he worked as an Assistant Professor of American civilization until 2010. Between 2010 and 2012, Diamond was a full research fellow at the [[Centre d'Etudes et de Recherches Internationales]] (CERI) at [[Sciences Po - Paris]], where he also taught a number of classes between 2007 and 2012. In 2012, he obtained his current position at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]].\n\nDiamond is a member of the editorial boards of the ''Revue fran\u00e7aise d'\u00e9tudes am\u00e9ricaines'' and ''The Sixties: A Journal of History, Politics and Culture'', and serves on the Board of Directors of the [[Fulbright Commission]] in France. He has been a featured speaker for the African Regional Services of the [[United States Department of State]], the United States Embassy in Paris, and the Consulate General of France in Chicago. He is currently working with the [[Institut Fran\u00e7ais]] of the [[French Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] as curator of \"City/Cit\u00e9: A Transatlantic Exchange,\" a program of international conferences that brings together researchers, artists, policymakers, and activists from the United States and France to engage in a dialogue about the current state of urban democracy and of the circumstances arrayed against the realization of democratic ideals.<ref>{{cite web|title=City/Cit\u00e9: A Transatlantic Exchange|url=https://fr.franceintheus.org/spip.php?article8237}}</ref> He has written [https://soundcloud.com/newberrylibrary/chicago-on-the-make-andrew-j-diamond extensively] and appeared regularly in both the French and American mainstream media on issues of race and inequality [http://www.liberation.fr/auteur/4247-andrew-diamond France and the United States].\n\n== Works ==\nHe is the author or co-author of a number of articles and books on the history of politics, race and political culture. His forthcoming book, ''Chicago on the Make: Power and Inequality in a Modern City'' (University of California Press, 2017) explores the \"link between race and neoliberalization at Chicago's grassroots over the 20th century\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Chicago on the Make: Power and Inequality in a Modern City|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=o4A0DwAAQBAJ&dq=andrew++J+diamond+opinion+piece&hl=fr&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref> He is also currently co-editing a collection of essays with [[Thomas Sugrue]] on the neoliberalization of US cities in the postwar era.\n\n== Major publications ==\nDiamond, Andrew J., ''Chicago on the Make: Race and Inequality in a Modern City'' (Berkeley and Los Angeles: University of California Press, 2017)\n\nDiamond, Andrew and Pap Ndiaye, ''Histoire de Chicago'' (Paris: Fayard, 2013)\n\nDiamond, Andrew, J., ''Mean Streets: Chicago Youths and the Everyday Struggle for Empowerment in the Multiracial City, 1908-1969'' (Berkeley et Los Angeles, University of California Press, 2009).\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[https://chipublib.bibliocommons.com/events/search/fq=branch_location_id:(15)&fq=types:(52ec53226ea5ed000000000f)/event/58dc0d29d13aea2200b0a0ec Acclaimed historian Andrew J. Diamond returns to CPL to discuss his new book, Chicago on the Make].\n\nChauvin, S. 2014. Chicago et l'exception urbaine am\u00e9ricaine. A propos des Andrew Diamond, Pap Ndiaye, Histoire de Chicago, Fayard in ''[http://www.laviedesidees.fr/Chicago-et-l-exception-urbaine.html La vie des id\u00e9es]''\n\nDuis, P.R., 2012. Mean Streets: Chicago Youths and the Everyday Struggle for Empowerment in the Multiracial City, 1908\u20131969.\n\nHinderer, M., 2010. Mean Streets: Chicago Youths and the Everyday Struggle for Empowerment in the Multiracial City, 1908\u20131969. By Andrew J. Diamond.(Berkeley: University of California Press, 2009. xviii, 396 pp.&nbsp; {{ISBN|978-0520-25747-4}}).\n\nPacyga, D. 2011 'Review of Diamond, Andrew J., Mean Streets: Chicago Youths and the Everyday Struggle for Empowerment in the Multiracial City, 1908-1969.'  [http://www.h-net.org/reviews/showrev.php?id=32973 H-Urban, H-Net Reviews.]\n\nWesley,JM. 2010. \"Andrew J. Diamond, Mean Streets: Chicago Youths and the Everyday Struggle for Empowerment in the Multiracial City, 1908\u20131969,\" ''The Journal of African American History'' 95(3-4), pp.&nbsp;451\u2013453.\n\nWieviorka, O. 2013. Critique: Chicaghetto.  ''[http://next.liberation.fr/livres/2013/11/27/chicaghetto_962442 Lib\u00e9ration]''\n\nYoung Jr, A.A., 2010. Mean Streets: Chicago Youths and the Everyday Struggle for Empowerment in the Multiracial City, 1908-1969.\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diamond, Andrew}}\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Paris-Sorbonne University faculty]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American expatriate academics]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Writers from Boston]]\n[[Category:Tufts University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:Historians from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People from Newton, Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Arnaudlef", "label": "safe", "comment": "Provided updated links and citations, updated the names of institutions, and updated the publications to show most recent works, awards received, and press coverage.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Diamond_(professor)"}
